        <!-- RAG Section -->
        <div id="rag" class="content-section">
            <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold text-slate-800 mb-6 border-b pb-2">Retrieval-Augmented Generation (RAG)</h2>
            <p class="mb-4 text-lg">A technique that enhances a foundation model's output by first retrieving relevant information from an external data source and then providing that information as context for the generation process.</p>
            <p class="citation">(Huyen, 2025, p. 253)</p>
            <div class="mt-6 p-4 bg-blue-50 border-l-4 border-blue-500 rounded-r-lg">
                <h3 class="font-semibold text-blue-800">Why is RAG important?</h3>
                <p class="mt-2 text-blue-700">It's crucial for mitigating model hallucinations, which often occur when a model lacks the necessary context to answer a query accurately. RAG remains critical even as model context windows expand, because application data needs often grow faster than context limits.</p>
                <p class="citation mt-2">(Lewis et al., 2020; Huyen, 2025, p. 255)</p>
            </div>
            
            <h3 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-slate-700 mt-8 mb-4">RAG Architecture</h3>
            <p class="mb-4">A standard RAG system consists of two primary components:</p>
            <ul class="space-y-4">
                <li><strong class="text-indigo-600">1. Retriever:</strong> Fetches information from an external source (e.g., a document database). Its functions include <strong>Indexing</strong> (structuring data) and <strong>Querying</strong> (finding relevant chunks).</li>
                <li><strong class="text-indigo-600">2. Generator:</strong> An LLM that uses the original prompt plus the retrieved context to produce the final response.</li>
            </ul>
            <p class="citation mt-4">(Huyen, 2025, p. 256)</p>

            <h3 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-slate-700 mt-8 mb-4">Retrieval Algorithms</h3>
            <div class="grid md:grid-cols-2 gap-6">
                <div class="p-4 border border-slate-200 rounded-lg">
                    <h4 class="font-bold text-xl mb-2 text-teal-700">Term-Based (Sparse) Retrieval</h4>
                    <p class="mb-2">Matches documents based on keywords (e.g., TF-IDF, Okapi BM25).</p>
                    <p><strong class="text-green-600">Pros:</strong> Fast, inexpensive. <strong class="text-red-600">Cons:</strong> Lacks semantic understanding.</p>
                    <p class="citation mt-2">(Robertson & Zaragoza, 2009, as cited in Huyen, 2025, p. 260)</p>
                </div>
                <div class="p-4 border border-slate-200 rounded-lg">
                    <h4 class="font-bold text-xl mb-2 text-purple-700">Embedding-Based (Dense) Retrieval</h4>
                    <p class="mb-2">Ranks documents based on meaning similarity using vector embeddings.</p>
                    <p><strong class="text-green-600">Pros:</strong> Captures semantic nuance. <strong class="text-red-600">Cons:</strong> More expensive and slower.</p>
                    <p class="citation mt-2">(Huyen, 2025, p. 262)</p>
                </div>
            </div>
            <p class="mt-4"><strong>Hybrid Search</strong> combines both methods to balance speed, cost, and accuracy, often using a term-based search followed by an embedding-based reranker.</p>
            <p class="citation mt-2">(Cormack et al., 2009, as cited in Huyen, 2025, p. 267)</p>

            <h3 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-slate-700 mt-8 mb-4">Retrieval Optimization & Scope</h3>
            <ul class="list-disc list-inside space-y-2">
                <li><strong>Chunking Strategy:</strong> How documents are split impacts quality. Overlapping chunks is recommended.</li>
                <li><strong>Query Rewriting:</strong> Using an LLM to reformulate ambiguous queries.</li>
                <li><strong>Contextual Retrieval:</strong> Augmenting chunks with metadata (title, summary) to make them more discoverable.</li>
                <li><strong>Beyond Text:</strong> RAG can be extended to <strong class="font-semibold">Multimodal</strong> data (images via CLIP) and <strong class="font-semibold">Tabular</strong> data (via Text-to-SQL workflows).</li>
            </ul>
            <p class="citation mt-2">(Huyen, 2025, pp. 268-274)</p>
        </div>

        <!-- Agents Section -->
        <div id="agents" class="content-section">
            <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold text-slate-800 mb-6 border-b pb-2">AI Agents</h2>
            <p class="text-lg mb-4">An agent is an entity that can perceive its environment and act upon it. In AI engineering, an agent uses an LLM as its "brain" to process information, create a plan, and execute actions using a set of available <strong class="text-rose-600">tools</strong>.</p>
            <p class="citation">(Russell & Norvig, 1995, as cited in Huyen, 2025, p. 275)</p>
            
            <h3 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-slate-700 mt-8 mb-4">Agent Planning & Execution</h3>
            <ul class="list-disc list-inside space-y-2">
                <li><strong>Decoupling Planning and Execution:</strong> Best practice is to generate a plan, validate it (with AI or human oversight), and then execute it to prevent wasted resources.</li>
                <li><strong>Reflection and Error Correction:</strong> High-performing agents use frameworks like <strong class="font-semibold">ReAct (Reason + Act)</strong> to iterate through a cycle of Thought, Action, and Observation, allowing them to learn from outcomes.</li>
                <li><strong>Control Flows:</strong> Plans can include sequential, parallel, conditional (if), and loop-based execution for more sophisticated tasks.</li>
            </ul>
             <p class="citation mt-2">(Huyen, 2025, pp. 282, 291, 293)</p>
            
            <h3 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-slate-700 mt-8 mb-4">Advanced Agent Architectures üèóÔ∏è</h3>
            <p class="mb-4">Effective agents often use complex patterns to decompose tasks:</p>
            <div class="grid md:grid-cols-2 gap-4">
                <div class="p-3 bg-slate-50 rounded-lg border"><strong>Prompt Chaining:</strong> A linear sequence of LLM calls.</div>
                <div class="p-3 bg-slate-50 rounded-lg border"><strong>Routing:</strong> An initial LLM call to classify intent and direct the query.</div>
                <div class="p-3 bg-slate-50 rounded-lg border"><strong>Evaluator-Optimizer Loop:</strong> A generator LLM and an evaluator LLM work in a feedback loop.</div>
                <div class="p-3 bg-slate-50 rounded-lg border"><strong>Orchestrator-Workers:</strong> A central LLM delegates sub-tasks to specialized worker LLMs.</div>
            </div>
            <p class="citation mt-4">(Anthropic, 2024)</p>

            <h3 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-slate-700 mt-8 mb-4">Best Practices for Tool Use</h3>
            <ul class="list-disc list-inside space-y-2">
                <li><strong>"Prompt Engineer" Your Tools:</strong> Tool definitions should be extremely clear, with examples and edge cases.</li>
                <li><strong>"Poka-yoke" (Mistake-Proof) Your Tools:</strong> Design tools to make it hard for the LLM to make common errors.</li>
                <li><strong>Start Simple and Iterate:</strong> Avoid over-engineering by starting with the simplest solution and adding complexity only when needed.</li>
            </ul>
             <p class="citation mt-2">(Anthropic, 2024)</p>

            <h3 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-slate-700 mt-8 mb-4">Memory in Agentic Systems</h3>
            <p>Agents require robust memory to manage information. This includes <strong class="font-semibold">Internal Knowledge</strong> (from training), <strong class="font-semibold">Short-Term Memory</strong> (the context window), and <strong class="font-semibold">Long-Term Memory</strong> (external storage like a vector database).</p>
            <p class="citation mt-2">(Huyen, 2025, p. 301)</p>
        </div>
        
        <!-- Protocols Section -->
        <div id="protocols" class="content-section">
            <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold text-slate-800 mb-6 border-b pb-2">AI Agent Protocols</h2>
            <p class="text-lg mb-4"><strong class="text-red-600">The Challenge:</strong> A lack of standardized communication methods hinders agent interoperability and scalability.</p>
            <p class="text-lg mb-4"><strong class="text-green-600">The Solution:</strong> AI agent protocols are standardized frameworks that define the rules, formats, and procedures for structured communication.</p>
            <p class="citation">(Yang et al., 2025, pp. 1, 6)</p>
            
            <h3 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-slate-700 mt-8 mb-4">Protocol Taxonomy</h3>
            <div class="grid md:grid-cols-2 gap-6">
                <div class="p-4 bg-blue-50 border-l-4 border-blue-500 rounded-r-lg">
                    <h4 class="font-semibold text-blue-800">1. By Object Orientation</h4>
                    <ul class="list-disc list-inside mt-2 text-blue-700">
                        <li><strong>Context-Oriented:</strong> Agent-to-resource interaction (e.g., MCP).</li>
                        <li><strong>Inter-Agent:</strong> Agent-to-agent interaction (e.g., A2A).</li>
                    </ul>
                </div>
                 <div class="p-4 bg-purple-50 border-l-4 border-purple-500 rounded-r-lg">
                    <h4 class="font-semibold text-purple-800">2. By Application Scenario</h4>
                    <ul class="list-disc list-inside mt-2 text-purple-700">
                        <li><strong>General-Purpose:</strong> Broadly applicable.</li>
                        <li><strong>Domain-Specific:</strong> Tailored for specific contexts (e.g., robotics).</li>
                    </ul>
                </div>
            </div>
            <p class="citation mt-4">(Yang et al., 2025, p. 7)</p>

            <h3 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-slate-700 mt-8 mb-4">The Agent Communication Trilemma</h3>
            <p class="mb-4">Protocol design involves a trade-off between three competing goals:</p>
            <div class="grid sm:grid-cols-3 gap-4 text-center mt-6">
                <div class="p-4 bg-slate-50 rounded-lg border shadow">
                    <h4 class="font-semibold text-xl text-slate-800">Versatility</h4>
                    <p class="mt-2 text-slate-600">Supporting diverse message types.</p>
                </div>
                 <div class="p-4 bg-slate-50 rounded-lg border shadow">
                    <h4 class="font-semibold text-xl text-slate-800">Efficiency</h4>
                    <p class="mt-2 text-slate-600">Minimizing cost and latency.</p>
                </div>
                 <div class="p-4 bg-slate-50 rounded-lg border shadow">
                    <h4 class="font-semibold text-xl text-slate-800">Portability</h4>
                    <p class="mt-2 text-slate-600">Ensuring the protocol is easy to implement.</p>
                </div>
            </div>
            <p class="citation mt-4 text-center">(Marro et al., 2024, as cited in Yang et al., 2025, p. 15)</p>
        </div>

